Background¶

This analysis utilizes data from the Boston Housing Study to advise a real estate brokerage firm on market value. The Boston Housing data is comprised of 506 census tracts and contains information on houses as well as their surrounding area. Using all available data points, except neighborhood, this analysis explores home value through various regression methods. Ultimately, one model is chosen and recommended to the real estate brokerage firm.

Data Initiation¶

We begin the analysis by reading in the data and performing some initial data exploration. These steps help to inform the scope of the exploratory data analysis section.

From the violin plot, we can more readily see that the median home value is just above 20. Moreover, we can see that the distribution is not symmetric. It is worth calling out that although the neighborhood variable was excluded from this analysis, that variable could add value in the future by helping to reduce the range of the home values considered, as they are very broad.

From the Charles River visual, we can see that homes on the Charles River have a wider distribution in median home value. This result makes sense, as location has the potential to increase home value. However, we can see that the median values are fairly similar.

In contrast, we see a very different trend in radial highways. From the univariate analysis, we could see that Radial Highways has a bimodial distribution. In the plot above, we can see that if the access to radial highways is above 20, then the median home value does not go above 20. On the other hand, if the access to radial highways is low, then there is a wider range in median home value. We can see that there is a higher concentration of data points near the home value median of approximately 20.

Thus, it seems like both of these predictors could be helpful in predicting median home value.

In [240]:
def corr_chart(df_corr):
    corr=df_corr.corr()
    #screen top half to get a triangle
    top = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
    top[np.triu_indices_from(top)] = True
    fig=plt.figure()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,15))
    sns.heatmap(corr, mask=top, cmap='coolwarm', 
        center = 0, square=True, 
        linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={'shrink':.5}, 
        annot = True, annot_kws={'size': 9}, fmt = '.2f')           
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right') # rotate variable labels on columns (x axis), add adjustment so text appears right by axis ticks
    plt.yticks(rotation=0) # use horizontal variable labels on rows (y axis)
    plt.title('Correlation Heat Map')   

corr_chart(boston_df)

<Figure size 432x288 with 0 Axes>

From the correlation matrix, there are many relationships that stand out. Here is a highlight:

  • rad (radial highways) and tax (tax rate) have a strong positive correlation at .91. Making sure that a model does not suffer from multicollinearity may be key here if both of these variables are included in a model.
  • mv (median value) has strong correlations with rooms (positive relationship) and lstat (socioeconomic status - negative relationship). Otherwise, the remaining correlations are weak to moderate. Most relationships are negative.
  • dis (employment centers distance) has a strong negative correlation with indus (industrial), nox (air pollution). and age (house age). This result may be due to the fact that the homes from this study are farther out in the suburbs or in areas that are now more built up.

Data Preparation¶

In this section, we prepare the data for modeling. As a first step, variables are standardized using the StandardScaler() function to help ensure that the ranges of values are similar for all variables.

To see if variable transformations are also needed, we examine the skewness and kurtosis values for each variable. Skewness is a measure of symmetry, while kurtosis is a measure of the height of the peak of a distribution. We are hoping to see values close to 0 for every variable, as this would indicate that a variable is normally distributed.

Model Building¶

In this section, three different models will be developed on a training set using an 80/20 split:

  • Linear regression
  • Ridge regression
  • Lasso regression

In addition to traditional goodness of fit statistics, these models will also be evaulated within a cross-validation design using root mean-squared error (RMSE).

Baseline Model: Linear Regression¶

In [337]:
lin_reg = LinearRegression()
lin_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)

#in reading documentation on cross val metrics, only neg_mean_squared_error is one 
#therefore, best to create our own metric and call that using cross_val_score
def rmse(y, y_pred):
        return np.sqrt(np.mean((y_pred - y)**2))
    
rmse_scorer = make_scorer(rmse, greater_is_better=False)

#run the cross validation
score = cross_val_score(lin_reg, X_train, y_train, cv=3, scoring=rmse_scorer)
print("CV RMSE results: ", -1 * score)
print("CV RMSE mean: ", -1 * np.mean(score))

CV RMSE results:  [0.54952181 0.53615681 0.49893526]
CV RMSE mean:  0.5282046270630971

From the cross validation results above, we can see that the mean RMSE across the 3-folds is .528. However, we can see that there is variability in the performance across the folds, as the range is from .499 to .550. These results will become more meaningful as we generate results from other methods. As it stands, we are merely just trying to gauge the performance of this model on data it has not seen before.

Next, we examine traditional goodness of fit statistics to determine the performance of this model.

In [376]:
#calculate GOF metrics as a summary - in future, should make this a function
lin_reg_yhat = lin_reg.predict(X_train)

#r-squared
lin_reg_rsquared = round(r2_score(y_train, lin_reg_yhat),3)

#MSE
lin_reg_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, lin_reg_yhat)

#RMSE
lin_reg_rmse = round(sqrt(lin_reg_mse),3)

#rounding MSE
lin_reg_mse = round(lin_reg_mse,3)

#MAE
lin_reg_mae = round(mean_absolute_error(y_train, lin_reg_yhat),3)

x = PrettyTable()
x.field_names = ["R-Squared", "MSE", "RMSE", "MAE"]
x.add_row([lin_reg_rsquared, lin_reg_mse, lin_reg_rmse, lin_reg_mae])
print(x.get_string(title="Linear Regression Training Set"))

+-----------------------------------+
|   Linear Regression Training Set  |
+-----------+-------+-------+-------+
| R-Squared |  MSE  |  RMSE |  MAE  |
+-----------+-------+-------+-------+
|   0.745   | 0.262 | 0.512 | 0.368 |
+-----------+-------+-------+-------+

It is worth pointing out that because our variables were centered and scaled, then the resulting goodness of fit statistics are scaled as well and not interpreted in thousands of 1970s dollars.

From the goodness of fit statistics table above, we can see that the R-squared value is fairly high at .745. However, we can see that there are differences in MAE and RMSE. For background, MAE is the average magnitude of errors, while the RMSE takes the square root of the squared difference between the residuals and fitted values. Therefore, RMSE gives more weight to values that are farther away from their actual value. If MAE and RMSE are close together or about equal, then we know that all the errors are of the same magnitude.

In our case, MAE and RMSE are not equal, which tells us that not all errors are of the same magnitude. As a step to improve model fit, residuals could be examined in greater detail to determine if there are influential points that should be removed.

Lastly, we examine residual plots to determine if this model meets the assumptions of linear regression (constant variance, normality).

In [344]:
lin_reg_resid = y_train - lin_reg_yhat

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize = (15,4))

pylab.show()

From the residual plots, we can see that the normality assumption is met, as the data points fall almost perfectly on the 45-degree line. The assumption of constant variance is not fully met. While the fitted line shows curvature, we can better wee that there are some outlier points that are pulling this line in a nonlinear fashion. Data points near the top and bottom of the Residuals vs Fitted Values should be removed.

Ridge Regression¶

Next, we generate a model using ridge regression. Ridge regression utilizes an L2 regularization, which is an additional constraint that helps with overfitting. In this model, the magnitude of the coefficients should be as small as possible.

In [345]:
ridge = Ridge(alpha=1)
ridge.fit(X_train, y_train)

#run the cross validation
score = cross_val_score(ridge, X_train, y_train, cv=3, scoring=rmse_scorer)
print("CV RMSE results: ", -1 * score)
print("CV RMSE mean: ", -1 * np.mean(score))

CV RMSE results:  [0.55007004 0.53590464 0.49819272]
CV RMSE mean:  0.5280558013738673

From the default ridge regression model (alpha = 1), we can see that the CV RMSE results are very similar to the linear regression results.

We examine some additional ridge regression model output by adjusting the alpha parameter. As the alpha parameter increases, coefficients move toward zero. Adjusting this parameter impacts training and test set performance.

Lasso Regression¶

An alternative model to Ridge regression is Lasso regression. This model uses an L1 regularization, which is more restrictive and creates some coefficients that are exactly zero. This type of model can be beneficial when there are a lot of predictors and only a few are thought to be important.

In [352]:
lasso = Lasso(alpha=1)
lasso.fit(X_train,y_train)

#run the cross validation
score = cross_val_score(lasso, X_train, y_train, cv=3, scoring=rmse_scorer)
print("CV RMSE results: ", -1 * score)
print("CV RMSE mean: ", -1 * np.mean(score))

CV RMSE results:  [1.04160383 1.0761126  0.91511899]
CV RMSE mean:  1.0109451392743987

From the default Lasso model, we can see that the CV RMSE results are way worse than the Ridge and Linear regression models. Therefore, it is likely that a different alpha parameter is needed to experience better training set results.

Right away, we can see that the alpha = 1 model makes all values equal to zero, which is not a helpful model. Model Selection¶

Now that we have explored each of the models on the training set, we need to now examine their performance on the test set to determine the optimal model. Because the Ridge and Lasso regression models each have a regularization parameter to help protect against overfitting, we are hoping to see that these models perform better on the test set.

From the goodness of fit statistics, we can see that the Lasso alpha = .01 model is the inferior model. The Ridge model does not seem to perform as best as the Linear regression or Lasso alpha = .0001 models.

Therefore, determining which model is superior between the Linear and Lasso alpha = .0001 models is not an easy decision. Gaining a better understanding of how the model will be used may help aid in a decision. That being said, it seems like the Lasso alpha = .0001 model will be superior in the long run, as it helps protect against overfitting by adding a regularization parameter. Additionally with this model, more parameters will have a coefficient of zero, meaning that less parameters are used in the model. In other words, in selecting a final model, the principle of parsimony plays a role, and the Lasso model will generalize better to new data due to its definition.

Summary and Conclusions¶

This analysis explored the Boston housing data set and generated three different predictive models using Linear, Ridge, and Lasso regression methods. While the performance across models was similar (if not identical) on the training set, the models showed some differences in performance on the test set. Ultimately, the Lasso regression model (with alpha parameter = .0001) was chosen as the best model due to its ability to protect against overfitting and generalize better to new data in the long run.

To help improve the fit of the model, some inspection should be done on influential points first and foremost. After this step, then the residual plots should be re-examined to ensure that the assumption of constant variance is met. Transforming variables with high relative skewness or kurtosis values (i.e, crim, lstat, dis) may also help to ensure that this assumption is met. These steps were not performed above due to time constraints.

Additionally, while cross validation using RMSE was used to understand how the models performed on new/unseen data, cross validation could be used to tune hyperparameters (i.e., alpha values) and help aid in the decision of which hyperparameters are best. Additional metrics, outside of RMSE, could then be used to evaluate models/hyperparameters and select the best performing model.

Also, while Elastic Net was not considered above, it could be considered in a next iteration, along with Linear, Ridge, and Lasso regression models. By adding more models to the mix, this step will help to ensure that the Lasso model is truly the best model.

Lastly, it would be helpful to have more context on the goals of this model, as this may inform if there are certain types of homes that should be removed altogether. For instance, while the neighborhood variable was removed from this analysis, it could be used as a proxy for data filtering, as median home value varies greatly by neighborhood. This type of extra analysis will help to improve model fit and ensure that the model generalizes well for the business problem.
